<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-912-494  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 912 494.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Nov 9 1989 v34 n23 p85(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Objects facilitate modular, reusable code: object-orientedprogramming. (includes related article on books aboutobject-oriented programming) (Technology Update)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Terry, Chris.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Object-oriented languages (OOLs) that are compiled rather thaninterpreted have become available only in the last few years,although object-oriented programming (OOP) has been around forsome time.andP;  OOP requires that data be associated with theprocedures that manipulate them: an object is a block of code witha data structure and all procedures required to create, modify,delete, import or export data elements.andP;  Objects need not know howthe data are represented or how to manipulate data elements, butan object can be an instance of a class of objects sharing commonproperties, and a class can inherit the attributes and propertiesof a more general class.andP;  Classes used to create individualobjects that behave in a similar way are arranged hierarchicallyin an object-oriented system: those at the top are general andthose at the bottom are specific.andP;  Several OOLs are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Object-Oriented LanguagesObject-Oriented ProgrammingProgram Development TechniquesSoftware DesignProgram Development ToolsSoftware Selection.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Multiple inheritance allows the class WINDOW to inherit graphicalaspects. (chart)For more information.... (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>